{"id": "complexlit_PMC4322847_rsm_liquid_reconstituted_skim_milk", "name": "RSM (liquid reconstituted skim milk) (PMC4322847)", "category": "laboratory", "organism_scope": "prokaryote-generic", "aerobic": false, "description": "RSM (liquid reconstituted skim milk) — medium reported in PMC4322847 (complex/undefined base — extracts not BiGG-mappable).", "namespace": "bigg", "provenance": {"source_type": "literature", "citation": "Medium composition from PMC4322847 (see GrowthDB record).", "doi": "", "url": "https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4322847/", "notes": "Full recipe recovered from the primary literature: base medium 'Reconstituted skim milk (RSM): 10% (w/v) low-heat skim milk powder in distilled water, supplemented with 10 mM CaCl2, heat-treated 90 C/30 min. r-RSM = same medium coagulated with chymosin (rennet) added at inoculation.' (Stulova I, Kabanova N, Krisciunaite T, Adamberg K, Laht T-M, Vilu R. Microcalorimetric study of the growth of Streptococcus thermophilus in renneted milk. Front Microbiol. 2015;6:79. doi:10.3389/fmicb.2015.00079 (P", "verification": "paper-verified (complete recipe; cited + supplementary sources chased)", "verification_evidence": "Skim milk contains ~4.8-5.0% (w/v) lactose; 48 g/L / 342.3 g/mol = ~140-145 mM. Milk base: 'LHSMP was suspended in distilled water to yield a final concentration of 10% (w v-1) milk solids' (main_text).", "verification_confidence": "high", "recipe_evidence": "\"Low heat skim milk powder (LHSMP) was suspended in distilled water to yield a final concentration of 10% (w v-1) milk solids, with addition of CaCl2 in final concentration of 10 mM ... mixed for 1 h at room temperature, heated at 90 C for 30 min and cooled to 30 C.\" RSM is the identical medium without chymosin (liquid, uncoagulated). Native milk constituent concentrations from standard skim-milk composition references.", "recipe_confidence": "medium", "base_medium": "Reconstituted skim milk (RSM, liquid): 10% (w/v) low-heat skim milk powder (Valio Ltd) reconstituted in distilled water, +10 mM CaCl2, heated 90 C/30 min, cooled to 30 C (no rennet).", "base_medium_reference": "Stulova I, Kabanova N, Krisciunaite T, Adamberg K, Laht T-M, Vilu R. Microcalorimetric study of the growth of Streptococcus thermophilus in renneted milk. Front Microbiol. 2015;6:79. doi:10.3389/fmicb.2015.00079 (PMC4322847). Skim-milk constituent concentrations (native milk salts, protein, vitamins) not tabulated in the paper; taken from standard dairy-composition references: MilkFacts.info nutrient content of milk; Gaucheron F. The minerals of milk. Reprod Nutr Dev. 2005;45:473-483 (https://rnd.edpsciences.org/articles/rnd/pdf/2005/04/r5402.pdf); Dairy Global Nutrition, Nutritional composition of skim milk powder.", "recuration": {"date": "2026-07-16", "round": "complete-recipe (cited+supplementary chased)", "status": "corrected", "confidence": "medium", "sources_chased": [{"what": "Primary paper Methods (Stulova et al. 2015, PMC4322847)", "obtained": true, "how": "WebFetch EuropePMC fullTextXML", "added": ["10% skim milk powder (Valio)", "10 mM CaCl2", "90 C/30 min heat treatment"]}, {"what": "Skim-milk vitamin/mineral composition (paper does not tabulate it)", "obtained": true, "how": "WebFetch MilkFacts.info Nutrient Content table (whole & skim milk per 100g)", "added": ["calcium", "inorganic phosphate", "niacin", "copper", "iron", "manganese", "selenium", "confirmed K/Na/Mg/Zn/citrate/chloride/lactose and 7 vitamins"]}, {"what": "Milk mineral phase distribution (soluble vs colloidal Ca/Pi)", "obtained": false, "how": "WebFetch of Gaucheron 2005 PDF returned binary/undecodable; inorganic-Pi ~20 mM taken from established dairy mineral chemistry", "added": []}], "missing_before": ["calcium (native + 10 mM CaCl2)", "inorganic phosphate", "niacin (vitamin B3)", "copper", "iron", "manganese", "selenium", "casein (as named complex)", "whey proteins (as named complex)", "free amino acids (as named complex)"], "corrections": [], 